  "prompt": "What is the diffusion of water through a membrane?",
  "response": "The diffusion of water through a selectively permeable membrane is called **osmosis**. Osmosis is a type of passive transport, meaning it does not require energy input from the cell. It occurs when water molecules move from an area of **higher water concentration** (or lower solute concentration) to an area of **lower water concentration** (or higher solute concentration), in order to equalize the concentrations on both sides of the membrane.\n\n### Key Points:\n- **Selectively permeable membrane**: Allows water to pass through but may restrict the movement of solutes.\n- **Water moves**: From a hypotonic solution (lower solute concentration) to a hypertonic solution (higher solute concentration).\n- **Osmotic pressure**: The pressure required to prevent water from moving across the membrane.\n- **Isotonic**: When solute concentrations are equal on both sides, there is no net movement of water.\n\nOsmosis is fundamental to many biological processes, such as maintaining cell turgor in plants and regulating fluid balance in animal cells.",
